Chimeric Reads Detection

BLAST

Nanopore libraries are prepared by ligation. This method is prone to the formation of chimeric artefacts where two or more reads are combined. To detect and split these reads, BLASTn-Short is used, looking for the pcr adapter sequence: AAGCAGTGGTATCAACGCAGAGT.

PCR Adapter detection (reads, #) 1488675.000
PCR Adapter detection (reads, %) 47.455
PCR Adapter detection + strand (reads, #) 1322201.000
PCR Adapter detection + strand, from raw reads (reads, %) 42.148
PCR Adapter detection - strand (reads, #) 1263618.000
PCR Adapter detection - strand, from raw reads (reads, %) 40.281

BLAST is looking for sequences with an identity to the PCR adapter sequence > 0.75%. The longer the match the more likely it is an actual PCR adapter (length: 23).

The PCR adapter sequences are expected to be at the read edges (5 and 3). Sequences located inside the read body can be associated to chimeric reads.

Ideal FLASH-seq ONT reads contain two PCR adapter sequences per read. One in Forward and one in Reverse orientation. Additional ones may be the reflect of chimeric artefacts.

Chimeric Segment

Chimeric reads are defined as having at least one PCR adapter in the read body (> 200 bp away of a read edge) and/or having >2 PCR adapters.

NB: Some reads may have a single internal adapter and be flagged as chimeric, despite showing a single segment. For this reason the mean number of ligated segments can theoretical be <2. These reads will follow the same path as regular chimeric segments. The splitting function will extract the appropriate segment from these reads. The mapping validation will verify if the split is appropriate or will flag them as problematic, later to be removed.

Reads from FLASH-seq ONT libraries are flanked by the PCR adapter sequences. We define three types of reads:

  • ==>: The read has one PCR adapter sequence in positive orientation.
  • <==: The read has one PCR adapter sequence at negative orientation.
  • ==><==: The read is flanked by two PCR adapter sequences in opposite orientations.

Chimeric reads follow the same logic but can harbor different combinations. For instance,

Mapping Validation

Banlist

Chimeric reads are split into segments. To validate the breakpoints, the chimeric segments/reads are mapped using minimap2.. The mapping of the chimeric reads (primary/supplementary) and segments (primary only) are compared. The overlap between the read/segment mappings is expected to be >80% or the breakpoints are considered as erroneous and the segment/read is flagged (=banlist), later to be discarded.

Putative chimeric segments (post-split) 435236.000
Mapping rate (%) 187.517
Problematic Reads (banlist, #) 26270.000
Problematic Reads (banlist, % chim. segs.) 6.036
Problematic Reads (banlist, % total) 0.837

Problematic reads - reasons:

  • In-silico chimeric = In silico chimeric reads not correctly split by Dorado/guppy.

  • No match chim. read/segm. Mappings = No match between the split segment primary alignment and the the read mapping (primary / suppl.).

  • Partial match chim. read/segm. Mappings = Match between the split segment primary alignment and the the read mapping (primary / suppl.) is below 0.8.

Overlap between the read and segments:

In silico-chimeric reads can occur when the second strand follows too quickly into the pore and is artificially attached to the first read. We have observed an increase of these events when the flowcell is overloaded (R10.4).

  • https://f1000research.com/articles/6-631/v2
  • https://github.com/nanoporetech/dorado

Dorado basecaller or duplex_tools can in theory remove these artifacts. However, in some cases they are left behind and represent an issue for this pipeline as they could be split into two distinct molecules, leading to over-counting. To exclude these events, the segment mappings (primary/supplementary) belonging to a single read are compared. If two segments originating from the same chimeric read are mapping at the same position (overlap >0%) in opposite orientations, they are considered as in-silico chimerics. The smallest alignment of the two is then flagged, later to be removed.

Barcodes - VSEARCH

The barcode primer position is searched in the first/last 200 bp of the read using vsearch:

CGACGCTCTTCCGATCTNNNNNNNNNNNNNAAGCAGTGGTATCAACGCAGAGT

Reads with at least one detected good barcode (%) 42.80

Only sequences displaying an identity >75% are retained:

The identity values returned by vsearch do not account for the length. We expected an average length around 53.

Barcode error rate.

Minimal levenstein distance of a barcode detected by vserach to a known barcode from the whitelist. Values above 2 can usually be corrected.

Optional UMI

UMI are detected and if necessary corrected at the demultiplexing stage.

Deletions are masked with N in monomeric UMI.

Trimeric UMI are handled corrected based on a whitelist. Uncertain trimer are masked with NNN. Please refer to the method section from the article.

Barcodes - Demultiplexing

The barcode extracted by vsearch are then processed. A barcode can be detected at the start or end of a read. In some instance, only the start or end barcode is retrieved. The following pipeline is applied:

  • Reads with a barcode perfectly matching the whitelist are identified and set aside (=PERFECT). If both start/end barcodes are detected only the reads with the same start/end barcodes are kept.
  • Imperfect barcodes are compared to the whitelist. Barcodes with a levenstein distance < 2 are corrected (=CORRECTED) to their closest counterpart.
  • If MODE=RESCUE, reads harboring different start/end barcodes with a single PERFECT one are corrected so that only the perfect match is kept (=RESCUE).
  • Reads displaying different start/end barcodes are discarded.
  • Reads without a detected CORRECTED, PERFECTED or RESCUE barcode are discarded.

The reads are then demultiplexed using these barcodes.

Reads with vsearch hit 1342796.000
Reads with correct barcode 1334269.000
Reads with correct barcode (%, total raw reads) 42.533
Reads with chimeric barcode pairs 8527.000
Reads with chimeric barcode pairs (%, total raw reads) 0.272

The barcode sequences are extracted from the reads and compared to the whitelist. To account for RT, PCR and sequencing errors, up-to two mismatches are allowed by default (levenstein distance).

The reads are expected to have the same barcode at both ends. However, in some reads, the barcode is only found at one end or there is a difference :
